"""
MKT Context Commentary — 1 Chronicles chapters 13–15
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1chronicles-13-15.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/1chronicles.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/1chronicles.json
- data/translation/glossary-hebrew.json

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch13: ark transport failure; "new cart" as inadvertent Philistine imitation; Perez-uzza etymology
- Ch14: Chronicler's success-formula (inquire of God vs. Saul who did not); Baal-perazim name theology
- Ch15: explicit Levitical correction of ch13 failure; founding of temple music; Michal as "daughter of Saul"
- Obed-edom identified as Levite (Gittite = from Gath-rimmon, a Levitical city), not Philistine
- Beeliada (ch14:7) retains Ba'al theophoric — Chronicler's historical fidelity despite later censorship in 2 Sam
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRON1 = {
  "13": {
    "1": '<p>David&rsquo;s consultation with &lsquo;commanders of thousands and hundreds&rsquo; reflects the traditional Israelite military-administrative structure. This opening act of consultation (<em>niwwāʿēṣ</em>) distinguishes David from Saul, who unilaterally handled sacred matters without proper consultation. The Chronicler adds this council scene to 2 Sam 6&rsquo;s account, emphasizing that the ark project began as a communal decision, not royal caprice.</p>',
    "2": '<p>&lsquo;If it seems good to you (<em>ʿālêkem ṭôb</em>)&rsquo; — a conditional formula seeking community consensus. &lsquo;The priests and Levites in their cities with pasturelands&rsquo; acknowledges the structure established in Joshua 21: Levites had designated cities throughout Israel (48 cities total) rather than a tribal territory. This reference situates the ark project within the proper Levitical framework even before it begins.</p>',
    "3": '<p>&lsquo;We did not inquire of it (<em>dĕrašnûhû</em>) in the days of Saul&rsquo; — <em>dāraš</em> (seek, inquire) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s most important theological term. The entire narrative of Chronicles is structured around the principle that seeking YHWH produces blessing, while failing to seek him produces disaster. Saul&rsquo;s failure to inquire was explicitly his fatal sin (1 Chr 10:14). David frames the ark project as a correction of Saul&rsquo;s neglect.</p>',
    "4": '<p>&lsquo;The thing seemed right (<em>kî-yāšar</em>) in the eyes of all the people&rsquo; — the assembly ratifies David&rsquo;s proposal. The near-universal agreement (&lsquo;all the assembly&rsquo;) is characteristic of the Chronicler&rsquo;s idealized portrayals of Israel&rsquo;s great moments: the whole community participates in acts of worship and covenant renewal. This pattern mirrors the later temple dedication under Solomon.</p>',
    "5": '<p>&lsquo;From Shihor of Egypt to the entrance of Hamath (<em>lĕbôʾ ḥămāt</em>)&rsquo; describes the ideal maximum extent of the land. The Shihor was an eastern branch of the Nile delta; Lebo-hamath was the northern boundary of the Promised Land (Num 13:21; 34:8; Josh 13:5). This formulation signals that David&rsquo;s gathering is pan-Israelite in its ideal scope — not the fractured monarchy of later years.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Kiriath-jearim (&lsquo;City of Forests&rsquo;), also called Baalah (originally a Canaanite site), was in Judah near the Philistine border. The ark had rested there since the Philistines returned it after the plagues of 1 Samuel 5–6 (1 Sam 7:1-2 mentions twenty years). Kiriath-jearim was one of four Gibeonite cities (Josh 9:17) — a non-Israelite city hosting the ark underscores the irregular situation David sought to correct.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The &lsquo;new cart&rsquo; (<em>ʿăgālâ ḥădāšâ</em>) is an inadvertent copying of Philistine practice. When the Philistines returned the ark, they placed it on a new cart drawn by two cows (1 Sam 6:7-8). That method worked for the Philistines — but the Torah prescribed that the Kohathite Levites carry the ark on their shoulders using poles (Num 4:15; 7:9); no cart was permitted. Israel unknowingly adopted the pagan transport method and would pay for it at Chidon.</p>',
    "8": '<p>&lsquo;David and all Israel were celebrating before God with all their might (<em>bĕkol-ʿōz</em>)&rsquo; — the festive language parallels 2 Sam 6:5. The celebration was genuine but uninformed: devotion does not substitute for obedience to the prescribed form. The Chronicler presents this as a cautionary tale about well-intentioned but improperly ordered worship — a concern central to post-exilic restoration debates about proper temple practice.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The threshing floor of Chidon (called Nacon in 2 Sam 6:6 — a textual variant between the two accounts, possibly different local names for the same site). Threshing floors were elevated, exposed platforms on hilltops; the cart&rsquo;s stumble on such terrain would be expected. The incidental geographic detail grounds the narrative in physical reality while the theological interpretation (the ark&rsquo;s holiness, not cart malfunction) frames the divine response.</p>',
    "10": '<p>&lsquo;The anger of the LORD was kindled (<em>wayyiḥar-ʾap yhwh</em>)&rsquo; — the idiom <em>ḥārâ ʾap</em> (lit. &lsquo;the nose burned&rsquo;) is the standard Hebrew expression for intense anger. Uzza touched the ark &lsquo;because the oxen stumbled (<em>šāmaṭ</em>)&rsquo; — his intention was protective. Yet Num 4:15 explicitly warned: &lsquo;they must not touch the holy things or they will die.&rsquo; Holiness in the ANE was dangerous; the boundary between sacred and common operated as an objective category, not merely a matter of intention.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The site name <em>Pereṣ-ʿuzzāʾ</em> (&lsquo;Breach of Uzza&rsquo;) preserves the event. <em>Pereṣ</em> (breach, breakout) is the same root as the name Perez (Gen 38:29, ancestor of David via Judah). The geographic etiology records that divine holiness broke out against an unauthorized approach. Notably, the same verb (<em>pāraṣ</em>) will appear in 14:11 (Baal-perazim) where YHWH breaks out against Israel&rsquo;s enemies — both uses are about divine irresistible force; the difference is the direction.</p>',
    "12": '<p>David&rsquo;s fear is theologically appropriate. &lsquo;How can I bring the ark of God to me?&rsquo; expresses the proper question: ark custody is a divine prerogative, not a royal one. The question implicitly acknowledges that proper procedure must be established before proceeding. The Chronicler uses this pause (ark at Obed-edom for three months) as a narrative breathing space for David to learn the correct Levitical protocol — which he then applies in chapter 15.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Obed-edom the Gittite: the designation &lsquo;Gittite&rsquo; has puzzled interpreters. In 1 Chr 15:18, 24, Obed-edom appears as a Levite in the gatekeeper role. One solution: &lsquo;Gittite&rsquo; means from Gath-rimmon, a Levitical city in Dan (Josh 21:24-25), not Philistine Gath. If so, Obed-edom was a Levite of appropriate lineage — meaning the ark landed with the right kind of custodian, just in an improvised setting rather than the appointed location.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Three months of blessing on Obed-edom&rsquo;s household establishes a narrative pattern: the ark&rsquo;s presence brings blessing to those who host it properly. The same pattern appears with Laban when Jacob was with him (Gen 30:27) and with Potiphar&rsquo;s household when Joseph served him (Gen 39:5). This blessing-through-the-bearer motif prepares for the permanent ark installation in Jerusalem: the whole city and kingdom will be blessed when the ark comes properly home.</p>'
  },
  "14": {
    "1": '<p>Hiram king of Tyre&rsquo;s embassy marks Tyre&rsquo;s emergence as the leading Phoenician city-state. Cedar from Lebanon was the prestige building material of the ancient Near East — used in Egyptian temples, Mesopotamian palaces, and later Solomon&rsquo;s temple. Tyre controlled the timber trade from the Lebanese mountains. Hiram&rsquo;s sending craftsmen (<em>ḥārāšê ʿēṣ</em>, carpenters/woodworkers) alongside materials reflects the patron-client diplomacy of the period: great kings signaled recognition by material support for palace-building.</p>',
    "2": '<p>&lsquo;David perceived (<em>wayyadaʿ</em>) that the LORD had established him as king&rsquo; — the verb <em>yādaʿ</em> here means covenantal/experiential knowledge, not merely intellectual recognition. Hiram&rsquo;s embassy functioned as external confirmation of divine election. The phrase &lsquo;his kingdom was highly exalted for the sake of his people Israel&rsquo; is significant: Davidic elevation serves a theocratic purpose — the king&rsquo;s greatness is for the people&rsquo;s sake, not his own glory.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The listing of multiple wives and children in Jerusalem reflects ANE royal practice: a large household demonstrated the king&rsquo;s status, and alliances were often sealed through marriage. The Chronicler lists this without the negative evaluation that Deut 17:17 implies (&lsquo;he must not take many wives&rsquo;). The focus is dynastic expansion; the sons listed will become the ancestors of royal lines tracked through Chronicles.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Shammua, Shobab, Nathan, Solomon — the first four sons of David&rsquo;s Jerusalem wives. Nathan (v4) is significant: he appears in Luke 3:31 as the ancestor of Mary&rsquo;s lineage of Jesus, while Matthew 1:6 traces Joseph&rsquo;s lineage through Solomon. The two Messianic genealogies in the NT diverge here, at David&rsquo;s sons, which Chronicles places at the founding of Jerusalem-based royalty.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Ibhar (&lsquo;he chooses&rsquo;), Elishua (&lsquo;my God is salvation&rsquo;), and Elpelet (&lsquo;God of deliverance&rsquo;) — three sons with theophoric names reflecting the theology of the Davidic court. Such names (composed with <em>ʾēl</em>) signal the religious orientation of the household; they are common in the Jerusalem-period onomasticon.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Nogah, Nepheg, and Japhia — three more sons. The list of thirteen sons at vv4-7 (parallel to 2 Sam 5:14-16) establishes the Davidic dynasty&rsquo;s breadth in Jerusalem. The Chronicler repeats this list from ch3:5-8, weaving dynastic continuity through the narrative. Large royal households in the ANE were both a sign of status and a political reality: each son represented a potential alliance or succession claim.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Elishama, <strong>Beeliada</strong>, and Eliphelet. <em>Beʿelyāḏāʿ</em> (&lsquo;Baal knows&rsquo;) retains the Ba&rsquo;al theophoric element here in Chronicles, while 2 Sam 5:16 reads &lsquo;Eliada&rsquo; (<em>ʾelyāḏāʿ</em>, &lsquo;God knows&rsquo;). The scribal substitution of <em>ʾēl</em> for <em>baʿal</em> in Samuel reflects the later aversion to Ba&rsquo;al names after the prophets&rsquo; campaigns against Ba&rsquo;al worship. The Chronicler&rsquo;s retention of the original form shows either access to an older source or a more historically precise tradition.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The Philistines&rsquo; response to David&rsquo;s anointing over all Israel reflects their prior political relationship. David had lived among the Philistines as a vassal of Achish of Gath (1 Sam 27; 29) — they knew him as a subject. His elevation to king of a united Israel ended that arrangement and threatened Philistine dominance of the coastal plain. &lsquo;All the Philistines went up to search for David&rsquo; — a punitive military expedition against a former vassal who had escaped their control.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The Valley of Rephaim (southwest of Jerusalem, near Bethlehem) was a strategic corridor between the Judean hills and the coastal plain. &lsquo;Rephaim&rsquo; (ancient giants) gave their name to this valley (Gen 15:20; Deut 2:11, 20); the term carried connotations of pre-Israelite peoples of unusual stature. The valley appears in Isaiah 17:5 as agricultural land; militarily, it provided an open approach toward Jerusalem from the southwest.</p>',
    "10": '<p>&lsquo;David inquired of God (<em>šāʾal dāwid bē&rsquo;lōhîm</em>)&rsquo; is the Chronicler&rsquo;s most important success formula. The verb <em>šāʾal</em> (ask, inquire) and <em>dāraš</em> (seek, inquire) together define the proper relationship between king and YHWH. Saul&rsquo;s defining failure was that &lsquo;he did not inquire of the LORD&rsquo; (1 Chr 10:14). David&rsquo;s consistent inquiry before battle explains his military success — not strategy or strength but divine consultation. YHWH&rsquo;s response: &lsquo;Go up, for I will give them into your hand.&rsquo;</p>',
    "11": '<p><em>Baʿal Pĕrāṣîm</em> (&lsquo;Lord/master of the breakthroughs&rsquo;) — the site name commemorates YHWH&rsquo;s victory. David&rsquo;s declaration &lsquo;God has broken through (<em>pāraṣ</em>) my enemies by my hand, like a breakthrough of waters&rsquo; names YHWH as <em>baʿal</em> (master/lord) of the <em>pereṣ</em> (breach). The term <em>pāraṣ</em> connects to <em>Pereṣ-ʿuzzāʾ</em> (13:11): the same divine breakout that killed Uzza for improper approach now destroys Israel&rsquo;s enemies. The direction of divine force depends on proper alignment with YHWH&rsquo;s will.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The Philistines abandoned their gods on the battlefield — a reversal of the ark capture (1 Sam 5: Philistines took Israel&rsquo;s sacred object). Now Israel burns the Philistines&rsquo; idols, following Deut 7:5 and 12:3 (&lsquo;burn their idols with fire&rsquo;). The Chronicler&rsquo;s version says &lsquo;burned with fire&rsquo; where 2 Sam 5:21 says &lsquo;David and his men carried them away&rsquo; — Chronicles conforms the action to Deuteronomic law, perhaps idealizing the event or preserving a different tradition.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A second Philistine incursion into the same valley. The Philistines&rsquo; persistence is a narrative setup for demonstrating that David did not rely on the first victory&rsquo;s momentum but again sought divine guidance. Each military campaign is treated as a new occasion for inquiry — the principle being not tactical self-reliance based on past success but renewed dependence on YHWH&rsquo;s specific direction.</p>',
    "14": '<p>&lsquo;Do not go up after them; go around behind them and come against them opposite the balsam trees&rsquo; — YHWH gives a different tactical instruction than in the first battle (there: direct assault; here: flanking maneuver with a specific signal). The variation emphasizes that divine guidance is not a formula but specific direction requiring attention. The balsam/mulberry trees (<em>bĕkāʾîm</em>) provided cover for the flanking approach and a visible signal point.</p>',
    "15": '<p>&lsquo;When you hear the sound of marching (<em>qôl haṣṣĕʿādâ</em>) in the tops of the balsam trees, then go out to battle&rsquo; — the sound in the treetops signals divine movement. The &lsquo;marching&rsquo; imagery evokes the divine warrior going before the army (cf. Judg 4:14: &lsquo;the LORD has gone out before you&rsquo;; Josh 10:14). YHWH acts independently and the human army follows the divine lead. The specific natural signal (wind in trees?) was both practically useful and theologically significant.</p>',
    "16": '<p>&lsquo;David did as God commanded (<em>ṣiwwâ</em>)&rsquo; — obedience to the specific divine word produces the specific result. From Gibeon (northwest of Jerusalem) to Gezer (on the coastal plain, at the entrance to the Shephelah) — a broad sweep that cleared the Philistine threat from the hill country approaches. Gezer was a major Canaanite city that would not be fully incorporated until Solomon&rsquo;s time (1 Kgs 9:16-17).</p>',
    "17": '<p>&lsquo;The LORD brought the fear (<em>pāḥad</em>) of him upon all nations&rsquo; — <em>pāḥad</em> (terror, dread) echoes the covenant promises of Deut 2:25, 11:25, and 28:10: the nations will fear Israel when YHWH is present. This fulfillment of Mosaic covenant promises signals that David&rsquo;s kingdom is the political realization of the covenantal vision. The Chronicler positions David&rsquo;s international reputation as a theological result of proper divine inquiry, not military prowess.</p>'
  },
  "15": {
    "1": '<p>&lsquo;David built houses for himself in the city of David and prepared (<em>kûn</em>) a place for the ark of God&rsquo; — the verb <em>kûn</em> (establish, prepare, make firm) is one of Chronicles&rsquo; key terms for proper arrangement. The tent prepared for the ark is not the Mosaic tabernacle (which remained at Gibeon, 1 Chr 16:39) but a new dedicated structure in Jerusalem. David&rsquo;s palace-building comes before the ark&rsquo;s installation, establishing royal context before sacred context.</p>',
    "2": '<p>&lsquo;No one ought to carry the ark of God except the Levites, for the LORD chose them&rsquo; — this explanatory verse is the Chronicler&rsquo;s theological commentary on the ch13 disaster. It cites Num 4:15 (Kohathites carry ark on shoulders with poles) and the divine election principle. The Chronicler adds this explicit correction not present in 2 Sam 6: the ark&rsquo;s improper transport was a violation of Torah, not merely bad luck. Knowing the rule is presented as the prerequisite for proper worship.</p>',
    "3": '<p>&lsquo;David assembled all Israel at Jerusalem&rsquo; — the third great assembly in the ark narrative (13:1-4 first; now again). The Chronicler&rsquo;s repeated emphasis on &lsquo;all Israel&rsquo; counters the north-south division that marked actual Israelite history. The inclusive assembly at Jerusalem is an ideal that the post-exilic community, reading Chronicles, could aspire to — Jerusalem as the gathering point of all twelve tribes in proper worship.</p>',
    "4": '<p>&lsquo;David brought together the sons of Aaron and the Levites&rsquo; — the distinction between priests (Aaron&rsquo;s sons) and Levites is fundamental to Chronicles&rsquo; ecclesiastical organization. The six Levitical clans that follow (vv5-10) represent the subdivisions established in the wilderness period: Kohath, Merari, and Gershon were Levi&rsquo;s three sons (Num 3:17); Elizaphan, Hebron, and Uzziel were Kohathite subclans (Num 3:27-30).</p>',
    "5": '<p>Kohath (Uriel the chief, 120 kinsmen) — the most prestigious Levitical clan because of their tabernacle assignment: Kohathites carried the holiest objects (ark, table of showbread, lampstand, gold altar, altar of incense) in the wilderness (Num 4:4-20). The Kohathite supervision of the ark&rsquo;s final installation is structurally appropriate. Uriel (&lsquo;my light is God&rsquo;/&lsquo;God is my flame&rsquo;) is also mentioned at 2 Chr 13:2.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Merari (Asaiah the chief, 220 kinsmen) — the Merarites were responsible for the tabernacle&rsquo;s physical framework: posts, crossbars, bases, and cords (Num 4:29-33). Their larger number (220 vs. Kohath&rsquo;s 120) reflects their role carrying heavier structural equipment in the wilderness. The name Asaiah (&lsquo;the LORD has made/acted&rsquo;) is a declarative theophoric name common in the Levitical onomasticon.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Gershom (Joel the chief, 130 kinsmen) — Gershon (also spelled Gershom) was Levi&rsquo;s firstborn but held a subordinate tabernacle role: screens, coverings, and curtains (Num 4:21-28), working under Ithamar the priest. The subordination of the firstborn in sacred hierarchy (younger Kohath having the holiest objects) is characteristic of the Torah&rsquo;s pattern: primogeniture does not determine sacred ranking.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Elizaphan (Shemaiah the chief, 200 kinsmen) — Elizaphan was son of Uzziel son of Kohath (Num 3:30), making this a Kohathite subclan. Moses&rsquo; appointment of Elizaphan as Kohathite leader (Num 3:30) was notable because it bypassed the sons of Moses himself. The Chronicler&rsquo;s careful listing of all six clans demonstrates that the ark&rsquo;s transport involves all branches of Levitical family in an organized hierarchy.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Hebron (Eliel the chief, 80 kinsmen) — Hebron was another Kohathite subclan (Num 3:27). The city of Hebron was a Kohathite city of refuge (Josh 21:11-13). This clan&rsquo;s smaller number (80) reflects the gradations within the Levitical structure. Eliel (&lsquo;God is my God&rsquo; or &lsquo;my God is El&rsquo;) is a name attested multiple times in Chronicles, suggesting it was common in Levitical/priestly families.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Uzziel (Amminadab the chief, 112 kinsmen) — Uzziel was the fourth son of Kohath (Exod 6:18; Num 3:27). Amminadab (&lsquo;my people are generous/noble&rsquo;) was a common name in priestly lineages (cf. Aaron&rsquo;s father-in-law Amminadab, Exod 6:23). The six Levitical groups total 862 men — a significant workforce mobilized for this one sacred act. The numerical precision signals bureaucratic organization appropriate to a post-exilic community concerned with proper institutional order.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Zadok and Abiathar were the two senior priests at this point, representing rival priestly lines. Zadok descended from Eleazar (Aaron&rsquo;s third son, after Nadab and Abihu died); Abiathar descended from Ithamar (Aaron&rsquo;s fourth son). Their later split over Solomon&rsquo;s succession (Abiathar supported Adonijah; Zadok supported Solomon, 1 Kgs 1) would result in Abiathar&rsquo;s expulsion and the exclusive Zadokite priesthood — the temple priesthood of the Second Temple period. Here they serve together under David.</p>',
    "12": '<p>&lsquo;Sanctify yourselves (<em>hithqaddĕšû</em>)&rsquo; — the Hithpael reflexive of <em>qāḏaš</em> (be holy, set apart) describes ritual self-purification. In the Mosaic period this involved: ritual bathing (<em>rāḥaṣ</em>), abstaining from sexual relations (Exod 19:15), and donning clean garments. The priestly manuals in Leviticus and Numbers elaborate the specific requirements. The Chronicler presents this purification as the prerequisite for handling sacred objects — not merely a formality but the practical means of maintaining the boundary between holy and common.</p>',
    "13": '<p>&lsquo;Because you Levites did not carry it the first time, the LORD our God broke out (<em>pāraṣ</em>) against us&rsquo; — David&rsquo;s explicit statement connecting the ch13 disaster to improper procedure closes the theological loop. The pronoun &lsquo;us&rsquo; shows corporate responsibility: the whole community suffered for the procedural violation, not only Uzza. This corporate guilt/blessing understanding is characteristic of the Chronicler&rsquo;s covenant theology — proper worship benefits the whole community; improper worship harms it.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The priests and Levites sanctified themselves collectively — the response to David&rsquo;s instruction is immediate corporate compliance. This stands in contrast to ch13, where the celebration began without proper preparation. The Chronicler presents this sanctification as the hinge moment: what follows (the successful transfer) results directly from this proper ordering. For the post-exilic community rebuilding temple worship, this sequence — purify, then proceed — was a living institutional principle.</p>',
    "15": '<p>&lsquo;The Levites carried the ark of God on their shoulders with the poles on it, as Moses had commanded according to the word of the LORD&rsquo; — the triple citation of authority (<em>ʿal-kitpām bammoṭôṯ ʿălêhem kiʾăšer ṣiwwâ mōšeh kidbar yhwh</em>) is emphatic. Contrast with 13:7: &lsquo;they carried the ark of God on a new cart.&rsquo; Now: shoulders, poles, Moses&rsquo; command, word of YHWH. The Chronicler signals through this formulation that success in worship requires alignment with the specific divine instructions, not improvised or borrowed methods.</p>',
    "16": '<p>David&rsquo;s instruction to appoint Levites as singers (<em>mĕšōrĕrîm</em>) establishes the institutional framework for temple music — one of the Chronicler&rsquo;s central concerns. &lsquo;Raising the voice with joy&rsquo; (<em>wĕhārîm qôl bĕśimḥâ</em>) — the musical celebration is both liturgical (<em>qôl</em> = voice/sound) and affective (<em>śimḥâ</em> = joy). Second Temple Judaism placed great weight on proper musical worship as a form of covenant faithfulness; this founding moment under David legitimizes that entire tradition.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Heman son of Joel, Asaph son of Berechiah, and Ethan son of Kushaiah — the three founding temple musicians. These names are attached to specific Psalms: Asaph is credited with Psalms 50 and 73–83; Heman with Psalm 88; Ethan (Jeduthun) with Psalm 89. The Chronicler treats these three as the musical equivalent of Aaron in priesthood: founding figures whose families carry the tradition. The threefold structure mirrors the three priestly classes under the high priest.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The second-rank Levites — eight names serve as subordinates to the three lead musicians. The graduated hierarchy (first-rank: Heman, Asaph, Ethan; second-rank: Zechariah and others) reflects the organizational structure the Chronicler traces throughout: sacred roles are ranked and assigned, not improvised. Jeiel, Shemiramoth, Jehiel, Unni, Eliab, Benaiah, and Maaseiah are among the names of this secondary rank. This detailed roster signals institutional legitimacy: the temple music was properly organized from its founding.</p>',
    "19": '<p><em>Mĕṣiltayim</em> (bronze cymbals) — percussion instruments used to mark the rhythm of the musical performance. Cymbals appear throughout ancient Near Eastern iconography in cultic contexts; they are mentioned extensively in Chronicles and Psalms (Ps 150:5: &lsquo;praise him with resounding cymbals&rsquo;). The bronze material (rather than iron) places them in the older metalworking tradition associated with the tabernacle vessels.</p>',
    "20": '<p><em>ʿal-ʿălāmôṯ</em> — the harps assigned to this group play &lsquo;upon alamoth.&rsquo; The term <em>ʿălāmôṯ</em> appears in the superscription of Psalm 46 and may designate a soprano or high-pitched register (&lsquo;virgins&rsquo; voices = high pitch?), or a specific musical mode. Ancient music theory distinguishes registers, and this technical term signals that the Chronicler or his sources had access to specialized musical knowledge from the temple&rsquo;s early period.</p>',
    "21": '<p><em>ʿal-haššĕmînîṯ</em> — &lsquo;upon the sheminith,&rsquo; appearing also in the superscriptions of Psalms 6 and 12. <em>Šĕmînît</em> means &lsquo;eighth&rsquo; — possibly an octave lower than the <em>ʿălāmôṯ</em> group, indicating a bass register. If <em>ʿălāmôṯ</em> = soprano and <em>šĕmînît</em> = bass, the Levitical choir had organized soprano-bass harmonic structure — a sophisticated arrangement signaled by these technical terms preserved in psalm superscriptions.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Chenaniah, &lsquo;chief of the Levites for the music (<em>hamaśśāʾ</em>)&rsquo; — the term <em>maśśāʾ</em> can mean either &lsquo;the lifting&rsquo; (of the voice in song) or &lsquo;carrying/burden&rsquo; (a technical musical direction). He was appointed because he &lsquo;was skilled (<em>mēbîn</em>) in it&rsquo; — the verb <em>bîn</em> (understand, be discerning) applied to musical leadership suggests this was a skilled profession requiring specific training, not merely enthusiasm. His role as director parallels the later role of the temple&rsquo;s musical leadership described extensively in Chronicles.</p>',
    "23": '<p>Berechiah and Elkanah served as &lsquo;gatekeepers for the ark&rsquo; — specialized security roles during the transit. Gatekeepers (<em>šōʿĕrîm</em>) in the Second Temple period controlled access to sacred spaces; here their role during the ark&rsquo;s procession is protective. Two gatekeepers for one ark establishes a paired security principle that the Chronicler traces throughout the temple service organization (ch26 elaborates the gatekeeper assignments).</p>',
    "24": '<p>Seven priests blow the <em>ḥăṣōṣĕrôt</em> (metal trumpets, distinct from the shofar) before the ark. Seven priests with trumpets echoes the Jericho narrative: seven priests with seven trumpets marching before the ark for seven days (Josh 6:4-6, 13). The deliberate numerical echo connects the ark&rsquo;s Jerusalem entry to Jericho&rsquo;s conquest — both are moments of decisive divine-human cooperation in securing sacred space. Obed-edom also appears as a gatekeeper, tying him to the ark narrative from his three-month hosting (ch13:14).</p>',
    "25": '<p>The assembly of &lsquo;David, along with the elders of Israel and the commanders of thousands&rsquo; mirrors the opening of ch13: the ark project ends with the same leadership coalition that initiated it. The Chronicler frames the entire ark narrative (chs13-15) as a democratically led, properly organized national event. The three months at Obed-edom (13:14) provided time for David to establish the correct Levitical protocol; now the properly organized procession can begin.</p>',
    "26": '<p>&lsquo;Because God helped (<em>ʿāzar</em>) the Levites who carried the ark&rsquo; — divine assistance is credited for the successful transport. The offering of seven bulls and seven rams (the Chronicler&rsquo;s addition to 2 Sam 6:13&rsquo;s &lsquo;oxen and fatlings&rsquo;) uses the number seven twice, emphasizing completeness and holiness. The Chronicler may have preserved a more detailed sacrificial record, or may have standardized the sacrifice to the sacred number. The offering follows the transport&rsquo;s success rather than preceding it — a thank offering rather than a propitiatory sacrifice.</p>',
    "27": '<p>David wore a &lsquo;robe of fine linen (<em>mĕʿîl bûṣ</em>)&rsquo; — <em>bûṣ</em> is white byssus linen, the material of priestly vestments (Exod 39:27-29; 2 Chr 5:12). By specifying &lsquo;fine linen&rsquo; where 2 Sam 6:14 only mentions &lsquo;a linen ephod,&rsquo; Chronicles elevates David&rsquo;s attire to full priestly quality. The Chronicler&rsquo;s David increasingly takes on priestly characteristics alongside royal ones — a theological statement about the Davidic king&rsquo;s role as mediator between the nation and its God.</p>',
    "28": '<p>&lsquo;All Israel brought up the ark&rsquo; — the climactic communal act. The instrumental list (<em>šôpār</em> [ram&rsquo;s horn], cymbals, harps, lyres; earlier: trumpets) provides a full picture of the sacred procession&rsquo;s sound. &lsquo;With shouting (<em>tĕrûʿâ</em>)&rsquo; — the ritual acclamation shout used at sacred moments (Ps 33:3; 89:15). The procession&rsquo;s audio texture — combination of winds, percussion, strings, and voice — reflects the full Second Temple musical establishment being narrated into existence.</p>',
    "29": '<p>Michal is identified as &lsquo;daughter of Saul&rsquo; (not &lsquo;wife of David&rsquo;) — the genealogical label marks her as representative of the rejected dynasty. Looking down from the window is a detail that recalls Sisera&rsquo;s mother waiting at the window (Judg 5:28) — a window figure associated with the defeated side. Her contempt for David&rsquo;s dancing reflects the Saulide perspective: kingly dignity requires reserve, not enthusiastic worship. The Chronicler (like Samuel) presents her contempt as spiritually blind — the proper response to the ark&rsquo;s return is the celebration she despises.</p>'
  }
}

